# WWW Documentation — User Manual for docs.liliflow.ai

**When a completed feature is added to the marketing feature list** (per `marketing-feature-list.mdc`), you **must also** create or update the corresponding **user-manual style documentation** in `_docs/www/` so the functionality is documented on **https://www.liliflow.ai/docs** (e.g. [workflow-builder](https://www.liliflow.ai/docs?article=workflow-builder)).

## Purpose

- **Audience:** End users, customers, and evaluators — people who use or evaluate the product.
- **Style:** User manual — how to use the feature, step-by-step, with clear headings and examples. Not internal dev docs or API reference.
- **Location:** `_docs/product/` is product/backlog; `_docs/www/` is the source for the public docs site.

## Where to add documentation

| Type of feature | Location | Example |
|-----------------|----------|---------|
| **High-level UX / getting started** (designer, library, templates, platform overview) | `_docs/www/Getting Started/` | `Drag-and-Drop Workflow Builder.md`, `Workflow Library and Templates.md` |
| **Step types or integration guides** | `_docs/www/` (top level) | `Web Crawling Steps.md`, `OpenSearch Steps.md`, `Advanced Steps.md` |
| **New capability that fits an existing doc** | **Update** the existing file (add a section or subsection) | Add "Enable/Disable Steps" to the Workflow Builder doc |

- Use a **new file** when the feature deserves its own article (e.g. a new step family or a major UX area).
- **Update an existing file** when the feature is a sub-capability (e.g. "enable/disable steps" inside the workflow builder doc).

## User-manual style (what to write)

Write so a user can **find and use** the feature without reading code or internal specs.

1. **Title and Last Updated**
   - Start with `# Feature or Page Title`.
   - Add **Last Updated:** YYYY-MM-DD (use the feature completion date).

2. **Overview**
   - Short paragraph: what this is and why a user would use it.

3. **How to access / get started**
   - Where in the UI (menu, URL, screen).
   - Prerequisites if any (e.g. crawler-service for Web Crawling).

4. **Core features / steps**
   - Break down into clear sections (e.g. "Visual Canvas", "Step Library", or per-step-type).
   - Use **step-by-step** where it helps (numbered lists).
   - Use **tables** for parameters, options, or quick reference.

5. **Examples**
   - Short examples (config snippets, UI paths) so users can copy or follow.

6. **Links**
   - Link to related docs (e.g. API, other articles) only when useful for the user.

## Examples of existing style

- **Getting Started:** `_docs/www/Getting Started/Drag-and-Drop Workflow Builder.md` — Overview, Accessing the Designer, Core Features (canvas, step library), Building Your First Workflow.
- **Step reference:** `_docs/www/Web Crawling Steps.md` — Overview table, Prerequisites, then per-step (Parameters, Output Variables, Example YAML).

## Checklist (when adding docs for a completed feature)

- [ ] New or updated file under `_docs/www/` (or `_docs/www/Getting Started/`).
- [ ] **Last Updated:** YYYY-MM-DD (completion date).
- [ ] User-manual tone: how to use, not internal implementation.
- [ ] Clear headings and structure (Overview, access, features, examples).
- [ ] If you added a new top-level doc, ensure the docs site can discover it (e.g. add to nav/index if the project has one).

